                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d169">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4/1234: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Acting Chairman of the American Delegation (<persName corresp="#p_GHS1"
                            type="to">Gibson</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-07-01T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 1, 1932—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>165. Your 293, July 1, 5 p.m. The point you have raised seems to be one of detail
                    suitable for adjustment in Geneva. It would not <pb facs="0372" n="252"
                        xml:id="pg_252"/> seem necessary to modify your draft speech or re-calculate
                    the quantitative chart, unless you should perceive positive advantages in so
                    doing.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
